    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Threat Guns Pose</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Phyllis Cohen letter, replying to a May 30 letter, says even firearms owned by law-abiding citizens can be dangerous</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A May 30 letter writer's assertion that firearms owned by law-abiding citizens pose no threat must not go unchallenged.</p>
        <p>With tragic frequency we hear of examples to the contrary: guns owned by householders or merchants that, because of carelessness or extreme emotion, kill innocent people, often the gun owners themselves or their loved ones.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A May 30 letter writer's assertion that firearms owned by law-abiding citizens pose no threat must not go unchallenged.</p>
        <p>With tragic frequency we hear of examples to the contrary: guns owned by householders or merchants that, because of carelessness or extreme emotion, kill innocent people, often the gun owners themselves or their loved ones.</p>
        <p>The vast majority of deaths by gunshot -- all of the accidental ones and many that are intentional as well -- would not occur by other means if the gun were not available.</p>
        <p>PHYLLIS COHEN  New York, May 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
